        <h2>Senses in Communication</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Task switching</strong> is a skill that most people only acquire through experience, practice and increasing expertise. When you are communicating as an OJTI to your student, they will <strong>take in information</strong> through the senses, primarily <strong>“sight”</strong> and “<strong>hearing</strong>”, with sight being the dominant of the two. As an OJTI if you are communicating to your student with an instruction or question, <strong>during a visually demanding traffic situation</strong>; an inexperienced student may not comprehend your communication fully, or partially, or misinterpret it. The student does not have the capacity to deal with both senses at the same time. The OJTI may need to actively <strong>intervene</strong> to “break” the visual link in order for the spoken communication to be received and understood.</p>

        <h2>How much information to provide?</h2>

        <p>As an OJTI trying to communicate with your student regarding a solution to a difficult tactical problem, bear in mind that you are the <strong>unconsciously competent</strong> controller (able to perform tasks competently without conscious effort) and that the student may still be <strong>consciously incompetent</strong> (does not understand or know how to do something). By virtue of your experience, you will be making <strong>links</strong> between the pieces of information that your student may not be able to. The way you communicate and how much information you provide will make a difference to whether the student will understand what is required of them.</p>

