        <h2>Perception and Expectation Bias</h2>

        <p>Perception is the way we <strong>interpret</strong> the information picked up by our senses and expectation bias can decide the outcome of that interpretation based on what we <strong>expected</strong> to happen.</p>

        <p class="">We sometimes see or hear what we want to see or hear and for different reasons. These could be:</p>

      </div>

      <div class="oj-lowlight pt-4">

        <div class="ians-column-wide-4">

          <ul class="oj-peb-container list-none pl-0" data-title="Perception and Expectation Bias">
            <li>
              <strong>Time pressure</strong> in assessing communication – rushed and hurried perception.</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Fear of failure</strong> – can affect through expectation bias. A structured, factual critique can be interpreted as a criticism.</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Cultural reasons</strong> – can affect expectation bias. Some cultures view challenges as potential threats.</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Previous experiences</strong> can produce avoidance of anything that resembles a previously bad experience even if it is not the same.</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Relationship with the person</strong> communicating with us. E.g. if we think the person communicating with us is trying to trick us, we can perceive the communication as “veiled” of “false”. If we have a sound relationship with the person communicating with us we do not have to interpret the real meaning behind the communication.</li>
          </ul>

        </div>
      </div>

