      <ul class="ians-column-wide-1 ians-grid-2 oj-guidelines">
        <li class="oj-notched">
          <strong>Think about your student</strong>
          <p>Ask yourself what they are telling you and why. </p>
        </li>
        <li class="oj-notched">
          <strong>Listen without interrupting</strong>
          <p>As an instructor, you will have heard the same thing time and again.  Many of us even try to finish the sentence for the student.  But interruptions may cause resentment. If you are listening for an opportunity to break in, you are not focused on the content of the speech.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="oj-notched">
          <strong>Give encouraging responses</strong>
          <p>Try to make these varied and meaningful.  Here are some examples of encouraging responses: "A lot of people have that problem", "It’s a matter of fine judgement", "Your idea is really interesting, try to take it a step further."</p>
        </li>
        <li class="oj-notched">
          <strong>Avoid unhelpful comments and “put&#8209;downs”</strong>
          <p>It is not helpful to be judgemental, e.g.  "That was wrong". Instead, try to be positive,  "In cases like that you may find it easier to ...". The wrong kind of comment discourages the student from talking. Put downs such as “Tut-tut!!” or “Oh dear!” will likely result in a fear of communication from your student.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>

