          <h2>Barriers to Communication</h2>

          <p>It’s important to recognise common problems preventing people from getting the message you are communicating.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="oj-barriers ians-column-wide-5 ians-grid-2">

          {# <hr class="oj-hr-barrier"> #}

          <div>
            <h3 class="oj-mt-8">
              <span>Distraction</span></h3>

            {% image "images/distraction.jpg", "Distraction"%}

            <p>We are in a hurry, or distracted by other things that are claiming our attention. <strong>Noises</strong>, <strong>mobile phones</strong> and <strong>passers-by</strong> are especially distracting. Try to choose the right time and place for important communications.</p>
          </div>

          {# <hr class="oj-hr-barrier"> #}

          <div>
            <h3>
              <span>Language</span></h3>

            {% image "images/language.jpg", "Language"%}

            <p>We fail to understand what is said because either the language, <strong>dialect</strong> or <strong>accent</strong> of the speaker is not our native one, or we are not familiar with all the <strong>professional vocabulary</strong>, 
  <strong>jargon</strong> or specialised group language.</p>

            <p>Use words that you think your student will understand and explain words and expressions that may be new. Try to speak a little more <strong>slowly</strong> and <strong>clearly</strong> if you think the student may have a problem with your pronunciation.</p>
          </div>

          {# <hr class="oj-hr-barrier"> #}

          <div>
            <h3>
              <span>Distortion</span></h3>

            {% image "images/distortion.jpg", "Distortion"%}

            <p>We misinterpret the words we hear because we have <strong>preconceived</strong> ideas about the situation, the people or cultures. So be aware of your preconceptions. Try to be objective and if you can’t quite do this, at least try and act <strong>objectively</strong>. </p>
          </div>

          {# <hr class="oj-hr-barrier"> #}

          <div>
            <h3>
              <span>Emotion</span></h3>

            {% image "images/emotions.jpg", "Emotions"%}

            <p>The message is distorted by our emotional attitude to a person, a situation or the words used.  Our culture and previous experience colour our perceptions of what people say and the way we speak to them.</p>

            <p>Communication can be inhibited by fear of the unknown, fear of authority, fear of looking foolish.  Many words have an <strong>emotional significance</strong>. The problem is that this may vary from person to person so bear this in mind, especially when you give feedback.</p>

            <p>Try to <strong>adapt</strong> your natural style to the student and think beforehand about how you’re going to express your ideas.</p>
          </div>

          {# <hr class="oj-hr-barrier"> #}

          <div class="oj-grid-span">
            <h3>
              <span>Hidden Agenda</span></h3>

            {% image "images/hiddenAgenda.jpg", "Hidden agenda"%}

            <p>The desire to communicate may not always be our <strong>strongest motive</strong>. </p>

            <p>For instance, we may want to:</p>

            <ul class="list-disc list-inside">
              <li>impress someone</li>
              <li>assert our “authority”</li>
              <li>win an argument, or</li>
              <li>make our point felt.</li>
            </ul>

            <p class="mb-12">So we concentrate on our <strong>thoughts and our motives</strong>, i.e. the hidden agenda, not on what we should be trying to communicate. Be aware of this possibility and restrain yourself when the problem occurs. As we say, sometimes you have to look at yourself in the mirror, figuratively speaking; and ask, are you bringing to the discussion something that has no place there?</p>
          </div>
        </div>
